  "opinion": "As a man who grew up in a small town in Kansas and now lives in Kansas City with my family, I've seen firsthand how science can be both a unifying force and a source of division. My perspective on the gender gap in science isn't one of academic jargon but of lived experience. When I was a child, my parents—my mother with a bachelor's degree and my father with upper secondary education—taught me that curiosity was the key to understanding the world. They didn't push me into a specific career path, but they did encourage me to ask questions, whether it was about how the stars worked or why the soil in our garden was so rich. Now, as an unemployed man in my late fifties, I've watched my children grow up in a world where science education often seems to favor boys over girls. I've noticed that in my community, girls are often steered toward more 'feminine' subjects like art and literature, while boys are encouraged to pursue engineering or physics. This isn't just a statistical issue; it's a cultural one. The gender gap in science isn't about innate ability but about the messages we send to young people. We should address it by creating more inclusive environments where girls feel safe to explore science without fear of judgment. In my volunteer work with local schools, I've seen how simple things like role models—people who look like the students and have achieved in science—can make a big difference. It's not about changing the curriculum but about changing the way we talk about science. We need to ensure that every child, regardless of gender, feels that they belong in the scientific community. The solution isn't complex; it's about empathy and understanding. If we can help girls see themselves as scientists, then we can build a more diverse and innovative future.",
